00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:02.040
to them in just a minute.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:05.690
First, I want to start off with
some words about this really

00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:08.690
important topic that
we're considering today.

00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:12.800
We will explore how ideas
of belonging, community,

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:16.850
and citizenship interact
both with our understanding

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:20.450
of disability and with
important policy questions

00:01:20.450 --> 00:01:22.550
related to disability.

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:26.810
We know from research and from
abundant anecdotal evidence,

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:30.650
that people with disabilities
often face multiple barriers

00:01:30.650 --> 00:01:36.530
to full societal inclusion, and
to freely and fully exercising

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:38.750
their citizenship rights.

00:01:38.750 --> 00:01:43.940
These barriers include stigma,
and exclusionary social norms,

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:49.280
inaccessible built environments,
prejudice, overt discrimination

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:51.170
and more.

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:53.960
People with disabilities,
also, are frequently

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:58.710
precluded from accessing
equal education, health care,

00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:01.310
and other critical benefits.

00:02:01.310 --> 00:02:06.920
This is both a civil rights
and a human rights issue.

00:02:06.920 --> 00:02:10.460
Here in the United States,
we've made some progress

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:12.740
in the realm of
legal protection.

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:16.820
It was 28 years ago that
Congress passed the Americans

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:21.650
with Disabilities Act of 1990
with strong, bipartisan support

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:23.480
in Congress--

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:26.140
both the Senate and the House.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:29.500
The ADA prohibited disability
based discrimination

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:32.620
in all areas of
public life, including

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:34.780
at school and at work.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:37.450
But we have not
fully conceptualized,

00:02:37.450 --> 00:02:43.120
much less realized, equality for
individuals with disabilities.

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:46.690
Anti-discrimination laws
like the ADA are necessary

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:48.520
and they're very important.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:53.060
But they're not sufficient to
ensure dignity and equality.

00:02:53.060 --> 00:02:55.300
This is partly because
we often fall short

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:59.260
when it comes to
implementation of the law.

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:02.320
But more fundamentally, it's
because '80s discrimination

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:06.430
laws do exactly what you
think they do, and not more.

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:10.330
They prohibit discrimination
and they demand equal treatment

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:12.250
before the law.

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:15.850
But as Michael has so
compellingly argued,

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:19.960
equal treatment before the law
can coincide with seriously

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:22.720
unequal opportunity.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:26.500
This is especially true
in the case of disability.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:30.340
To achieve true equality
and full inclusion,

00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:32.920
we need a much broader
set of policy measures

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:37.780
and other levers of
global and local change.

00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:40.000
Our speakers today will
highlight the breadth

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.270
and the complexity of these
and other critical issues

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:46.990
at the intersection of
disability and citizenship.

00:03:46.990 --> 00:03:49.540
And they'll explore
how we, as a society,

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:53.480
can make meaningful progress
at the international level,

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:57.700
at the national level,
and yes, here at Harvard.

