00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:54.734
are all dynamic
and really exciting

00:16:54.734 --> 00:16:55.900
you're going to learn a lot.

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:59.880
And I would say, this really,
for me, is an opportunity

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:03.090
to really dig deeper
into what does it really

00:17:03.090 --> 00:17:06.839
mean for Harvard
and universities

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:09.210
around the United States
and around the world

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:12.780
to really begin to get in
a more forthright way what

00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:14.760
it is that we're talking about?

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:17.680
And I just want to
add a little caveat.

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:19.560
While the Americans
with Disabilities Act

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:23.760
came about in 1990, section
504 of the Rehabilitation act

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:26.730
came about in 1973.

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.520
And let me just say that every
university in the United States

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:32.430
community college, college,
has had the obligation

00:17:32.430 --> 00:17:36.880
to do what we're talking
about today since 1973.

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:39.850
And so I think we need to
put that into perspective,

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:42.930
that this is not a
28-year-old requirement,

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:45.060
it's something that's
much longer than that.

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:53.550
- As a young person, when I
was in college one of the most

00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:55.620
memorable events I had.

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:58.640
I worked in a volunteer
program for the Worcester--

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:01.780
you've got to be from
Worcester to say Worcester--

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:05.100
Massachusetts of arc.

00:18:05.100 --> 00:18:09.390
And I was working with a
group of parents who had kids

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:11.670
who had multiple disabilities.

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:14.790
And they were petitioning
the Worcester public schools

00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:18.900
for a class for
their kids in 1970.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:23.320
And the Worcester
public schools said, no.

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:27.910
And for me that brought up
a whole issue of belonging.

00:18:27.910 --> 00:18:31.130
I thought all kids
went to school.

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:32.950
And for me, it was
a great epiphany

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:37.930
that actually not all kids went
to school as recently as 1970.

00:18:37.930 --> 00:18:42.400
So this issue of belonging rang
true to me as, at the time,

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:48.520
being an emerging gay
identity person, closeted,

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:51.710
but trying really
hard to get out.

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:54.100
And so Judy and I have
discussed this quite--

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:55.900
this whole fundamental
question, when

00:18:55.900 --> 00:19:00.090
you're talking about
citizenship, of who belongs.

00:19:00.090 --> 00:19:01.770
Your thoughts on that Judy?

00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:06.300
- So Tom relates to
learning in the 1970s,

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:08.700
that not all children
were in school,

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:10.380
and I was a product of that.

00:19:10.380 --> 00:19:14.680
So I'm from Brooklyn, I lived
in Berkeley for about 18 years.

00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:17.130
But I have to say that if
I hadn't lived in Brooklyn

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:19.730
I wouldn't be the
advocate I am today.

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:25.880
And when I was born in 1947,
my parents were immigrants.

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:28.910
And my mother took me to
school when I was five.

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:32.000
But there were no
laws in the 1950s

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:35.160
and the principal said
I was a fire hazard.

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:37.250
And so was not allowed
to go to school.

00:19:37.250 --> 00:19:40.700
But told my mother not
to worry, because they

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:43.040
would send a teacher
to a house, and they

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:45.920
did for 2 and 1/2 hours a week.

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:48.740
Not for kindergarten, for
the first, second, third

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:50.660
and a half of the fourth grade.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:54.830
And then I was
granted a screening

00:19:54.830 --> 00:19:56.540
by the Board of
Education in New York.

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:59.450
I had to go to a
school for a week,

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:04.640
be observed, have an evaluation,
come before a committee that

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:06.290
made the decision
as to whether or not

00:20:06.290 --> 00:20:09.950
you got to go to a
segregated, second rate,

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:11.390
educational program.

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:15.650
But I passed and I
got into this program.

00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:18.584
And one of the important
things about that was it

00:20:18.584 --> 00:20:20.000
was the first time
that I was ever

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.110
meeting other disabled people.

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:25.460
So while I had had my disability
since I was 18 months old,

00:20:25.460 --> 00:20:27.500
and I had polio so I
was in the hospital

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:29.160
and I met people there.

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:33.150
But I hadn't really been
with a group of peers,

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:35.620
other disabled individuals.

00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:40.490
I need to also say that
as a 9-year-old going

00:20:40.490 --> 00:20:43.670
into segregated classes
in a regular school,

00:20:43.670 --> 00:20:47.960
there were also children 16, 17,
and 18 years old in my class.

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:51.350
So what I learned very
early on was, at that time

00:20:51.350 --> 00:20:52.970
in New York City--

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:59.740
again no laws-- the children
in the special Ed classes

00:20:59.740 --> 00:21:03.130
stayed there until they
were 21 years old, and then

00:21:03.130 --> 00:21:05.650
were expected to go to
sheltered workshops.

00:21:05.650 --> 00:21:08.140
It was my mother organizing
with other mothers that

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:10.450
got the Board of
Education to make

00:21:10.450 --> 00:21:12.850
high schools accessible
in New York City

00:21:12.850 --> 00:21:15.040
so that I did, in
fact, not go back

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:17.300
onto home instruction
for high school,

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:19.644
but was able to go to school.

00:21:19.644 --> 00:21:22.060
I think one of the important
parts of the stories that Tom

00:21:22.060 --> 00:21:25.480
and I are saying right now,
is the fact that outside

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:29.380
of families who had kids with
disabilities, who were working

00:21:29.380 --> 00:21:31.660
on getting children
into school, there

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:37.187
was not a lot of
concern being expressed.

00:21:37.187 --> 00:21:39.520
The fact that disabled children
were not going to school

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:42.130
was really not a major issue.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:44.810
And for those children
who were in school,

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:47.020
there was not really
a lot of work going on

00:21:47.020 --> 00:21:51.340
to determine whether or not we
were getting the same education

00:21:51.340 --> 00:21:55.750
as children in the same school
that I finally got to go to.

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:59.837
And I think that really speaks
to the low expectations.

00:21:59.837 --> 00:22:02.170
And the reason why I think
the issue of low expectations

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:03.620
is really important.

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:05.860
And a lot of work that Tom
and I did in the Clinton

00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:10.180
administration really was
and still is addressing

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:12.670
the issue of low expectations.

00:22:12.670 --> 00:22:15.280
Because you're not
able to really move

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:19.390
to a higher level of discussion
if the majority of people

00:22:19.390 --> 00:22:23.470
in the world really have
not yet been convinced

00:22:23.470 --> 00:22:26.547
that we as disabled people
have the same rights as others.

00:22:26.547 --> 00:22:28.630
And I think one of the
other really pivotal issues

00:22:28.630 --> 00:22:33.390
about belonging is so many
disabled people do not identify

00:22:33.390 --> 00:22:35.140
as having a disability.

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:39.710
And they don't have identity
first images of themselves.

00:22:39.710 --> 00:22:43.900
We don't see ourselves
as a community in the US

00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:46.600
and around the world
yet, as really being

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:48.700
a political and dynamic force.

00:22:48.700 --> 00:22:51.130
A lot of work is going
on in that regard,

00:22:51.130 --> 00:22:53.740
but I think it's fair to
say that one out of four

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:56.140
people in the United
States have a disability,

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:59.500
and one out of four of
those disabled people

00:22:59.500 --> 00:23:02.110
do not really come
forth with pride

00:23:02.110 --> 00:23:05.320
to talk about who we are
as disabled individuals.

00:23:05.320 --> 00:23:08.080
Many people have
invisible disabilities.

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:12.340
The stigma around invisible
disability is very significant.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:15.970
And I think regardless of
what university I speak at,

00:23:15.970 --> 00:23:19.420
I hear the same stories
over and over again

00:23:19.420 --> 00:23:22.940
about the difficulty of feeling
a part of the universities.

00:23:22.940 --> 00:23:25.300
Yes, progress is
being made, statements

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:29.080
that are being made by
faculty and others that really

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:33.740
push people against the
wall and make it difficult

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:35.520
for them to move forward.

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:39.900
So I think the
issue of belonging.

00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:43.040
The issue of being able to
look more deeply at points

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:46.190
like lack of education,
which around the world

00:23:46.190 --> 00:23:47.880
is still a major issue.

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:51.530
And in the US, although
children are in school,

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:54.950
there is still, as we
know, large percentages

00:23:54.950 --> 00:23:58.280
of disabled children who are not
getting the level of education

00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:01.700
they need, or not getting the
support they need and are still

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:02.720
highly stigmatized.

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:09.000
- One of the things that one
of my wonderful experiences

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:13.410
teaching here at Harvard is
when I started, when I came here

00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:16.260
as a faculty member,
I was teaching courses

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:18.120
on inclusive education.

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:22.290
And I thought I'd be
teaching primarily

00:24:22.290 --> 00:24:26.160
to non disabled teachers,
which is the case still,

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:27.540
about inclusive practice.

00:24:27.540 --> 00:24:31.290
But the wonderful thing that
I began to see in my classes

00:24:31.290 --> 00:24:33.570
where there were so many
students with disabilities

00:24:33.570 --> 00:24:34.920
who were in my classes.

00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:39.430
And when I was a student here
in the '80s they weren't here.

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:43.890
And so one of the things that my
students who have disabilities,

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:45.900
and some who don't
have disabilities,

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:47.970
who are very much
interested in addressing

00:24:47.970 --> 00:24:51.330
this intergenerational question
that this institute is going

00:24:51.330 --> 00:24:54.630
to be talking about,
of situating themselves

00:24:54.630 --> 00:24:58.690
in the world and how
do they make change?

00:24:58.690 --> 00:25:01.000
I use you as an
example all the time.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.840
Because one of the things
that you have done,

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:06.349
Judy, and I'd like you to
speak a little bit about this,

00:25:06.349 --> 00:25:07.890
is that you've worked
on the outside.

00:25:07.890 --> 00:25:09.790
You took over a
federal building,

00:25:09.790 --> 00:25:11.880
remember secretary
Riley used to say that.

00:25:11.880 --> 00:25:14.640
My assistant secretary took
over a federal building

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:18.410
and now she's the Assistant
Secretary of Education.

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:25.030
[APPLAUSE]

00:25:25.030 --> 00:25:27.530
You've been on the outside,
you've been on the inside.

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:30.680
I've only been on the inside,
really, you know that.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:34.460
And I'd like your thoughts
about that, outside, inside,

00:25:34.460 --> 00:25:36.410
and what advice
you'd give younger

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:40.010
people with disabilities about
how to situate themselves?

00:25:40.010 --> 00:25:43.610
- So I worked 20 years
in nonprofit world,

00:25:43.610 --> 00:25:51.140
and in 1993 when I went to work
for the Clinton administration,

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:56.890
I had to go in with the real
conscious effort knowing

00:25:56.890 --> 00:26:01.880
that I was going into a world
of mainly non disabled people.

00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:08.050
And that was really something
that caused me a lot of thought

00:26:08.050 --> 00:26:11.890
about whether I really wanted
to go work, not only in a--

00:26:11.890 --> 00:26:14.590
I mean education was a
relatively small bureaucracy

00:26:14.590 --> 00:26:18.550
at that point, with almost
5,000 staff around the country.

00:26:18.550 --> 00:26:21.820
It's unfortunately
smaller today.

00:26:21.820 --> 00:26:23.110
But what would that be like?

00:26:23.110 --> 00:26:26.890
Because I had worked
in disability rights

00:26:26.890 --> 00:26:29.110
organizations for 20 years.

00:26:29.110 --> 00:26:33.400
And it was a very important,
empowering experience for me

00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:37.960
to be able to be a
part of the development

00:26:37.960 --> 00:26:40.852
of the independent living
movement and the disability

00:26:40.852 --> 00:26:41.560
rights movements.

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:44.350
First in New York, with
friends setting up a group

00:26:44.350 --> 00:26:47.470
called disabled in action,
then going out to California

00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:49.960
and being involved in
setting up the first center

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:52.240
for independent
living in Berkeley.

00:26:52.240 --> 00:26:54.790
And then going on with
friends to set up the world

00:26:54.790 --> 00:26:56.620
Institute on Disability.

00:26:56.620 --> 00:27:00.190
And I'd been a number of
nonprofit boards and dealing

00:27:00.190 --> 00:27:02.200
with disability, non disability.

00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:05.140
I also was on a board at that
point for the over '60s clinic.

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.510
So from an intergenerational
perspective,

00:27:07.510 --> 00:27:10.420
I was involved in issues
around aging and aging

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:13.030
and disability when
I was young myself.

00:27:13.030 --> 00:27:16.120
When I made the decision to
go work in the department,

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:20.860
I knew that one of the reasons I
was going to take this position

00:27:20.860 --> 00:27:24.730
was because of my fervent
belief that government

00:27:24.730 --> 00:27:28.370
needed to be responsible to
the disability community.

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:30.970
And in the case of the
Office of Special Education

00:27:30.970 --> 00:27:33.400
and rehabilitative
services, to parents who

00:27:33.400 --> 00:27:35.360
had children with disabilities.

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:36.970
And as some of
you the room know,

00:27:36.970 --> 00:27:41.230
there's been a lot of contention
between the parent community

00:27:41.230 --> 00:27:43.150
and the disability community.

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:46.420
Some in the disability
community feeling

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:51.550
that the role of parents
needs to be held in check.

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:57.130
And one of my big beliefs has
been that the role of parents

00:27:57.130 --> 00:27:58.180
is really critical.

00:27:58.180 --> 00:28:00.430
It needs to be age
appropriate, et cetera.

00:28:00.430 --> 00:28:02.780
But parents are the
ones who are going

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:05.570
to be giving the first
messages to their children.

00:28:05.570 --> 00:28:10.960
So if parents can be exposed
to strong, disabled individuals

00:28:10.960 --> 00:28:14.440
who have been able to fight
the battles and move forward,

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:16.900
that's a good role
model for parents.

00:28:16.900 --> 00:28:19.390
And so when I came
into the department

00:28:19.390 --> 00:28:22.922
and was lucky to find
Tom and recommend him

00:28:22.922 --> 00:28:24.880
to the secretary and the
president to be hired,

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:29.110
and the Rehabilitation Services
Administration and the National

00:28:29.110 --> 00:28:31.510
Institute on Disability and
Rehabilitation Research.

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:37.470
It was important for me to
assemble a team of advocates

00:28:37.470 --> 00:28:40.380
who were expert and
knowledgeable in their areas,

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:43.530
but who were not afraid
of bucking the system.

00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:46.590
Because you know it'd be very
easy to come into government

00:28:46.590 --> 00:28:50.490
and really play the game,
and not really remember

00:28:50.490 --> 00:28:54.420
where we all came from, and why
we were coming into government.

00:28:54.420 --> 00:28:56.640
And I think we were very
privileged at that time

00:28:56.640 --> 00:29:00.540
that the Clinton administration
really hired strong advocates

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:04.890
with disabilities who today's
administration wouldn't even

00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:08.280
blink an eye at, let alone
consider for a position.

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:11.320
And quite frankly, the Bush
administration didn't either.

00:29:11.320 --> 00:29:13.800
I think the Obama
administration carried forward

00:29:13.800 --> 00:29:17.040
what the Clinton administration
had been doing in many ways.

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:24.420
But what I learned
early on was that when

00:29:24.420 --> 00:29:28.110
we were dealing with
the re-authorization,

00:29:28.110 --> 00:29:30.540
my close friends
on the outside were

00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:32.880
people from the disability
rights education and Defense

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:33.810
Fund.

00:29:33.810 --> 00:29:36.510
And they were doing great
work in their education

00:29:36.510 --> 00:29:37.950
with disabled kids.

00:29:37.950 --> 00:29:39.600
And there was no
way that I was going

00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:42.600
to be involved in working
on the re-authorization

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:45.810
without bringing in some of the
strongest advocates, including

00:29:45.810 --> 00:29:48.561
people like Julie Landau
who's here in Massachusetts,

00:29:48.561 --> 00:29:50.685
and a very strong advocate
in the area of education

00:29:50.685 --> 00:29:52.500
with disabled kids.

00:29:52.500 --> 00:29:55.450
And we had meetings
and we had discussions.

00:29:55.450 --> 00:29:59.490
And one day, I got a call
from the Assistant Secretary

00:29:59.490 --> 00:30:04.557
of civil rights, Judith Winston.

00:30:04.557 --> 00:30:05.640
- Oh Yeah, Judith Winston.

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:06.360
General counsel.

00:30:06.360 --> 00:30:07.830
- General counsel, sorry.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:09.930
Who said to me that
one of her staff

00:30:09.930 --> 00:30:13.530
was concerned because I
had told them to please

00:30:13.530 --> 00:30:16.590
call one of these lawyers
as we're moving forward

00:30:16.590 --> 00:30:18.510
developing our proposals.

00:30:18.510 --> 00:30:21.180
Because I thought, OK, we
need to know what everybody

00:30:21.180 --> 00:30:23.210
thinks not just the lobbyists.

00:30:23.210 --> 00:30:25.890
And I said, don't worry,
things will be fine.

00:30:25.890 --> 00:30:28.357
Everybody will learn to
work and play together.

00:30:28.357 --> 00:30:30.690
And at the end of the day,
that's exactly what happened.

00:30:30.690 --> 00:30:33.030
So what do I tell young people?

00:30:33.030 --> 00:30:35.010
I tell, not necessarily
young people,

00:30:35.010 --> 00:30:39.270
what do I tell people
who are thinking

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:42.030
about moving into government?

00:30:42.030 --> 00:30:44.370
I believe it's really
important that when

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:47.940
you move into government, you
have a strong set of principles

00:30:47.940 --> 00:30:49.410
of what you believe in.

00:30:49.410 --> 00:30:51.540
That you're knowledgeable
and that you

00:30:51.540 --> 00:30:56.400
will learn in your job, but that
when you move into these jobs

00:30:56.400 --> 00:31:00.960
if you have a disability,
it is really important

00:31:00.960 --> 00:31:02.820
that you don't forget that.

00:31:02.820 --> 00:31:06.570
Just like as we
advance diversity

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:10.240
across the board for
gender, sexual orientation,

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:14.200
race, socioeconomic issues,
we as disabled individuals

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:16.330
who have cut across
all those groups

00:31:16.330 --> 00:31:18.930
need to remember that one
of the reasons we are coming

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:24.246
to the table is because we need
to represent a group of people

00:31:24.246 --> 00:31:28.740
who in fact are currently
insignificantly represented.

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:32.100
So we really have a
responsibility, in my view,

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:33.280
to make sure that happens.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:36.090
And when you come to a
university like Harvard,

00:31:36.090 --> 00:31:39.300
where you're exposed to so
much, the issue of disability

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:43.110
being integrated, not just to
the students and faculty who

00:31:43.110 --> 00:31:46.290
themselves have disabilities,
but really into the curricula

00:31:46.290 --> 00:31:47.760
across the board.

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:50.400
I mean in my view,
we should no longer

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:54.930
be having discussions about
requirements since 1973

00:31:54.930 --> 00:31:56.310
on accessibility.

00:31:56.310 --> 00:31:59.280
We should be digging
deep into how

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:04.590
is disability supposed to be
integrated into the curricula?

00:32:04.590 --> 00:32:06.420
And we are not there yet.

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:11.250
And that's, for me, why this
meeting is so important.

00:32:11.250 --> 00:32:14.070
I want to expect
that the bathrooms

00:32:14.070 --> 00:32:19.050
on every floor in a building are
accessible, which they're not.

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:22.350
That a podium is accessible.

00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:26.160
Basic things for me
to feel like I belong,

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:29.220
is that we are
really integrated,

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:31.860
and these issues are
ones that are not just

00:32:31.860 --> 00:32:35.940
being discussed in a
separate silo on disability,

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:38.160
that they are being
discussed across the board

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:39.780
when looking at diversity.

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:42.210
And I think Tom and
I did it really,

00:32:42.210 --> 00:32:46.440
we really worked hard on that
when we were at education.

00:32:46.440 --> 00:32:50.250
We went way beyond just
the mammoth amount of work

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:52.440
that we had to do on
the re-authorization,

00:32:52.440 --> 00:32:55.800
but in the department
itself we worked really hard

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:58.710
on getting disability
integrated across efforts.

00:32:58.710 --> 00:33:01.950
So we worked hard with the
bilingual education office,

00:33:01.950 --> 00:33:03.950
because the bilingual
education office,

00:33:03.950 --> 00:33:06.360
there are a lot
of disabled kids.

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:08.190
And they were not
getting served.

00:33:08.190 --> 00:33:10.680
We worked with the
vocational education office.

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:12.930
We got those staff
and others to begin

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.030
to think about
how did disability

00:33:15.030 --> 00:33:17.380
fit into their portfolio.

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:19.980
And when they were
monitoring what was going on,

00:33:19.980 --> 00:33:21.250
how were they looking at that?

00:33:21.250 --> 00:33:24.450
And how could we do
collaborative monitoring

00:33:24.450 --> 00:33:25.530
within the department.

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:27.930
And we were going out
to states to address

00:33:27.930 --> 00:33:29.380
many of these issues.

00:33:29.380 --> 00:33:33.690
So my message is, disability
is not yet a part of diversity

00:33:33.690 --> 00:33:36.840
as it should be, that
is your obligation

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:38.760
to make sure that
universities in fact

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:41.070
live up to their obligations.

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:44.580
And then it is your obligation,
in my view, when you leave here

00:33:44.580 --> 00:33:48.060
whatever job you're getting, is
that if you have a disability

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:50.170
or if you believe
that disability

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:52.080
is a part of the
diversity agenda,

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:54.780
you need to not let that
fall off to the side.

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:57.360
You need to identify
friends and colleagues who

00:33:57.360 --> 00:34:01.080
you can go to and speak to like
I've done, to ask people am I

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:02.160
a Martian?

00:34:02.160 --> 00:34:05.140
Which I had a good friend who
unfortunately passed away,

00:34:05.140 --> 00:34:06.930
but I would go
and speak with her

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:08.310
when weird things would happen.

00:34:08.310 --> 00:34:11.850
And I'd say, Katie
am I a Martian?

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:17.790
I kind of get back on the page
that I wasn't and move forward.

00:34:17.790 --> 00:34:19.650
- One of the things
that I think, I mean I'm

00:34:19.650 --> 00:34:21.360
totally biased in
this assessment,

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:24.239
but you've been the most
effective assistant secretary

00:34:24.239 --> 00:34:26.909
we've had period.

00:34:26.909 --> 00:34:29.820
And when I look at the outside,
inside question and the advice

00:34:29.820 --> 00:34:32.190
to younger people,
one of the things

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:39.010
that I think contributed to your
success was on the human level,

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:41.179
no pun intended.

00:34:41.179 --> 00:34:43.560
No, and I can
remember one anecdote

00:34:43.560 --> 00:34:46.469
that crystallized it for me.

00:34:46.469 --> 00:34:49.199
We were having a meeting with
the Republicans on the Hill,

00:34:49.199 --> 00:34:51.150
the Republicans were in charge.

00:34:51.150 --> 00:34:54.690
And all of a sudden, I see
Judy wheel over to the corner

00:34:54.690 --> 00:34:58.740
and your mother had just passed,
and one of the staffers mothers

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:00.240
had just passed,
and the two of you

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.520
were having a cry
over in the corner.

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:04.770
A conservative Republican.

00:35:04.770 --> 00:35:08.370
And I said, you know, Judy
can get anything done.

00:35:08.370 --> 00:35:12.040
Because on the human level,
you related to people.

00:35:12.040 --> 00:35:14.590
It wasn't just that this
was the right thing to do.

00:35:14.590 --> 00:35:17.700
It was you know,
how can you possibly

00:35:17.700 --> 00:35:20.880
oppose me because of who, you
know, because of the person

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:21.790
you were?

00:35:21.790 --> 00:35:25.320
And I think people
don't recognize

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:27.110
the importance of that.

00:35:27.110 --> 00:35:30.610
I mean, I think I'm an
extrovert, for those of you who

00:35:30.610 --> 00:35:33.390
don't know me.

00:35:33.390 --> 00:35:37.490
On the Myers-Briggs,
I'm way off the charts.

00:35:37.490 --> 00:35:42.400
And so I love to talk to people.

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:46.100
I love to learn from people
and hear people's stories.

00:35:46.100 --> 00:35:49.517
And when, I always
get emotional too.

00:35:49.517 --> 00:35:51.100
I was at a meeting
yesterday and there

00:35:51.100 --> 00:35:54.940
was a woman, a student
here, who was getting

00:35:54.940 --> 00:35:56.500
emotional about
something and I said,

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:59.050
I get emotional all the time
so don't worry about it.

00:35:59.050 --> 00:36:01.480
But I think stories
are very important.

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:05.700
I think regardless of this
history you're telling,

00:36:05.700 --> 00:36:08.280
people need to hear stories.

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:12.030
They need to understand today
we're discussing disability.

00:36:12.030 --> 00:36:15.460
And again, disability
cuts across race,

00:36:15.460 --> 00:36:18.270
socioeconomic status,
da da da da da da da.

00:36:18.270 --> 00:36:20.220
So we need to hear
people's stories

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:22.680
about good and bad things.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:24.990
People need to be
able to express

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:27.570
the pain that they're
feeling when not feeling

00:36:27.570 --> 00:36:29.070
like they belong.

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:32.550
When asking for things
that should in fact not

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:36.000
have to even be asked for,
but are not being given,

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.740
and having to figure out
how do you move forward

00:36:38.740 --> 00:36:40.650
in asking those stories?

00:36:40.650 --> 00:36:44.070
Why were the hearings,
well, I guess stepping back

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:47.220
to the Section 504.

00:36:47.220 --> 00:36:51.856
After that provision of the
Rehabilitation Act was passed,

00:36:51.856 --> 00:36:53.730
a gentleman named John
Wodash who some of you

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:58.610
may know who worked in the
Department of Justice, first

00:36:58.610 --> 00:37:00.480
at health education and welfare.

00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:03.660
When 504 came out
it was a small piece

00:37:03.660 --> 00:37:06.630
of legislation, 40 some words.

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:08.510
And nobody knew
what it was going

00:37:08.510 --> 00:37:11.970
to mean not to
allow discrimination

00:37:11.970 --> 00:37:13.590
for an entity that
was receiving money

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:15.130
from the federal government.

00:37:15.130 --> 00:37:18.090
So they went around the
country and they held meetings

00:37:18.090 --> 00:37:20.100
and they talked to
disabled people.

00:37:20.100 --> 00:37:22.680
Justin Dart did
the same thing when

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:24.180
the ADA was moving forward.

00:37:24.180 --> 00:37:26.520
He went around the
country to every state

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:29.250
and had people
tell their stories.

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:32.230
Because in the area
of discrimination,

00:37:32.230 --> 00:37:35.280
not a lot of people believed
that discrimination was

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:37.890
pervasive in the United States.

00:37:37.890 --> 00:37:40.110
Maybe it happened here and
maybe it happened there,

00:37:40.110 --> 00:37:42.870
but you know, nobody
really meant it.

00:37:42.870 --> 00:37:45.030
Nobody really meant to
say you are a fire hazard

00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:46.410
and you couldn't go to school.

00:37:46.410 --> 00:37:47.910
Nobody really meant
that you weren't

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:49.200
going to go to high school.

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:51.840
Nobody really meant that you
weren't going to get a job.

00:37:51.840 --> 00:37:53.720
Well that was all bullshit.

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:59.367
But I mean, let's
be real, maybe some

00:37:59.367 --> 00:38:01.200
of the issues around
discrimination and race

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:04.320
and disability are different
because if you're god fearing

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:07.530
and no one is supposed
to do anything

00:38:07.530 --> 00:38:10.030
bad to a disabled person.

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:12.600
So it wasn't
intentional or whatever.

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:23.180
But the reality is, we need
to be able to assert ourselves

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:29.450
in a way which allows us
to give people permission

00:38:29.450 --> 00:38:32.720
to tell their stories
and to listen and to do

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:34.370
more than just listen.

00:38:34.370 --> 00:38:36.860
So a lot of what every
one of the speakers

00:38:36.860 --> 00:38:39.950
today will be talking
about, or if you

00:38:39.950 --> 00:38:42.220
talk to them on the
side will tell you,

00:38:42.220 --> 00:38:45.195
is that people call
and ask questions.

00:38:45.195 --> 00:38:46.320
People want to talk to you.

00:38:46.320 --> 00:38:48.269
They want to tell their story.

00:38:48.269 --> 00:38:50.060
And if it's something
great that's happened

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:51.390
they want to tell it.

00:38:51.390 --> 00:38:55.100
But if they're having a problem,
they want you to listen.

00:38:55.100 --> 00:38:57.630
They want you to
help find a solution.

00:38:57.630 --> 00:38:59.960
They may have the solution.

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:02.030
And in many cases, they do.

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:05.420
And in fact, what they need
is your moral encouragement

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:07.460
to enable them to go forward.

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:08.810
It's the am I a martian?

00:39:08.810 --> 00:39:11.390
No, you're not, go fight
for what you believe in.

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:13.130
I'll be here for you to do that.

00:39:13.130 --> 00:39:14.810
We'll be here.

00:39:14.810 --> 00:39:18.110
Why is it important that we
have a strong disability rights

00:39:18.110 --> 00:39:20.750
movement that's not only
in the United States,

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:22.880
but that's an
international movement?

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:26.840
It's because our
stories are so the same.

00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:30.740
The unfortunate truth is,
our stories are so the same.

00:39:30.740 --> 00:39:32.960
They may be different
because in the United States

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:36.290
we've had our laws longer
than in some other countries,

00:39:36.290 --> 00:39:41.360
but the level of
discrimination, segregation,

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:45.980
feeling of being not a part
of a community, not belonging

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:48.160
are across the board.

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:52.870
It is important to say
that that is progressing.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:55.750
This convening would
not be happening today

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.470
if it weren't for the fact
that Michael and Cheri and Tom

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:03.580
and other people here at Harvard
and students and the Radcliffe

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:07.270
Institute didn't recognize
that this was important.

00:40:07.270 --> 00:40:10.060
But listen to people's stories.

00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:13.840
Allow people to feel that
they are a part of a movement.

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:16.160
Encourage people
to feel that they

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:19.150
are and part of a movement,
that their voices are important.

00:40:19.150 --> 00:40:22.240
And I mentioned briefly
earlier the issue

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:26.740
of invisible disability,
because so many people have

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:28.960
invisible disabilities,
whether it's

00:40:28.960 --> 00:40:32.080
a learning disability
or ADD or diabetes

00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:35.320
or epilepsy or cancer
or a severe back problem

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:38.410
or whatever the hundreds
of labels might be,

00:40:38.410 --> 00:40:40.870
those individuals need
to recognize that they

00:40:40.870 --> 00:40:43.090
are protected by the law.

00:40:43.090 --> 00:40:46.930
And that in fact, their
voices are important.

00:40:46.930 --> 00:40:49.390
And getting people with
invisible disabilities

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:54.520
to disclose, to feel like it's
safe to disclose and discuss it

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:58.560
and to come together as a
group is very empowering.

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:01.330
And it's something that
I think produces success

00:41:01.330 --> 00:41:03.760
and I feel like I'm
one of the people,

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:06.550
like many in this room,
who really encourage

00:41:06.550 --> 00:41:08.800
people to tell their stories.

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:10.660
That we value their
stories, and we

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:14.170
value them being able
to overcome adversity

00:41:14.170 --> 00:41:16.700
that they're dealing with
through story and support.

