00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:33.830
Given the political
climate that exists today

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:36.690
and the laws we
have on the books,

00:41:36.690 --> 00:41:44.210
you know, ADA, IDEA,
section 504, Rehab Act,

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:47.900
where do you think legal
enforcement or lawsuits fits

00:41:47.900 --> 00:41:51.730
in in this particular time?

00:41:51.730 --> 00:41:57.870
- I think we've always had to
be concerned about litigation.

00:41:57.870 --> 00:42:00.330
By that, I mean
one of the concerns

00:42:00.330 --> 00:42:05.220
when 504 was first moving
into implementation

00:42:05.220 --> 00:42:10.030
and the ADA is, we
wanted, and still want

00:42:10.030 --> 00:42:14.950
to make sure that there is
an educated group of lawyers,

00:42:14.950 --> 00:42:18.280
and that disabled people
and family members also

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:21.850
learn about the law because
it's important that we are

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:24.310
thoughtful and not frivolous.

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:27.100
And I think I, like
everyone in this room,

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:31.390
is deeply concerned about
appointments to the Supreme

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:37.610
Court and about appointments to
the courts in general because

00:42:37.610 --> 00:42:40.310
of the conservative nature.

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:43.220
And I don't want to say
that being conservative

00:42:43.220 --> 00:42:48.470
means you're anti disability
until proven otherwise,

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:52.910
but I am very
concerned that we need

00:42:52.910 --> 00:42:54.410
to be more strategic than ever.

00:42:54.410 --> 00:42:57.710
And in order to be more
strategic than ever,

00:42:57.710 --> 00:43:04.280
it really does mean that
faculty and students need

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:08.870
to really understand
disability rights laws,

00:43:08.870 --> 00:43:11.960
need to understand what
the laws do and don't say,

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:14.450
need to understand
case law, need

00:43:14.450 --> 00:43:17.030
to be able to look at
how to build forward

00:43:17.030 --> 00:43:19.940
so that we don't lose things.

00:43:19.940 --> 00:43:24.530
And I think we should
also be at a point

00:43:24.530 --> 00:43:31.400
where there are stronger
voices through academia that

00:43:31.400 --> 00:43:35.600
understand these issues
and that are strongly

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:41.360
working to ensure that when
we are dealing with filing

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:45.090
complaints, mediation, going
to court, federal courts,

00:43:45.090 --> 00:43:48.080
state courts
whatever, that we are

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:52.100
able to have some meaningful
discussions about what

00:43:52.100 --> 00:43:55.460
some of the challenges are
so that we can be educating

00:43:55.460 --> 00:43:57.770
not just those at
the universities,

00:43:57.770 --> 00:44:00.260
but at law
conferences, et cetera.

00:44:00.260 --> 00:44:03.000
Because I think disabilities,
as we've been saying,

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:06.650
still much too absence of it,
discourse is really important.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:09.740
And looking at disability
as a civil rights issue,

00:44:09.740 --> 00:44:13.310
we need to be working across the
board with other civil rights

00:44:13.310 --> 00:44:15.856
communities in a more
in-depth meaningful way.

00:44:15.856 --> 00:44:17.480
And I think people
like Andy and Perata

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:20.944
will be able to speak about
some of that later today,

00:44:20.944 --> 00:44:22.610
but I think it's a
very important issue.

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:27.670
When do we want to open this up?

00:44:27.670 --> 00:44:30.090
Do we want to open this up now ?

00:44:30.090 --> 00:44:32.280
We open this up now?

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:34.678
I think there are two people
