00:44:37.750 --> 00:44:40.150
So questions, comments?

00:44:44.420 --> 00:44:46.379
- Judy, this
question is for you.

00:44:46.379 --> 00:44:47.420
My name is Gavin Chhabra.

00:44:47.420 --> 00:44:50.420
I am a person with
severe visual impairment.

00:44:50.420 --> 00:44:54.380
You mentioned a couple
of interesting points

00:44:54.380 --> 00:44:58.310
about the fact that low societal
expectations and prejudicial

00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:00.940
attitudes are much
more widespread,

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:03.560
and the experiences of
people with disabilities

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:06.440
worldwide are converged.

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:09.260
So often, an antidote
to that, you also

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:13.460
mentioned that you have to have
positive images and stories

00:45:13.460 --> 00:45:17.060
which are positive of people
fighting and overcoming

00:45:17.060 --> 00:45:18.810
the disability.

00:45:18.810 --> 00:45:22.010
How do you kind of
walk this tightrope

00:45:22.010 --> 00:45:24.290
that the expectation
levels don't

00:45:24.290 --> 00:45:25.910
get blown out of proportion?

00:45:25.910 --> 00:45:29.900
For instance, you know, like
the media portrayal often

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:33.170
is of this super crip
person who has a--

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:35.930
who is quote, unquote this
inspirational [INAUDIBLE]..

00:45:35.930 --> 00:45:38.180
So how do we kind
of guide ourselves

00:45:38.180 --> 00:45:42.350
from setting the right
discourse if I may say so?

00:45:42.350 --> 00:45:45.637
And the reason why I ask this
is because in the case of India,

00:45:45.637 --> 00:45:47.720
which has one of the largest
population of persons

00:45:47.720 --> 00:45:50.870
with disabilities, just
recently in 2015 the government

00:45:50.870 --> 00:45:53.960
was talking about accessibility
rights based discourse

00:45:53.960 --> 00:45:55.640
on one hand, and
on the other hand

00:45:55.640 --> 00:45:59.060
it kind of labeled
persons with disabilities

00:45:59.060 --> 00:46:03.717
who were severely stigmatized
as devined bodied individuals.

00:46:03.717 --> 00:46:05.300
And the reason why
they said that they

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:07.940
are devined bodied
individuals is the idea

00:46:07.940 --> 00:46:12.140
is to give them positive
connotation to disability.

00:46:12.140 --> 00:46:16.670
To say that they are much
better than regular humans.

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:20.480
So how do we do not blow
it out of proportion

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:23.442
and how do we humanize this
whole debate if I may say so?

00:46:23.442 --> 00:46:25.400
- I do you think we're
much better than others.

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:29.330
It's a well-kept secret.

00:46:32.120 --> 00:46:34.010
Thank you very much
for your question.

00:46:34.010 --> 00:46:40.220
And let me say, that I feel it
is very important that people

00:46:40.220 --> 00:46:42.040
dream big.

00:46:42.040 --> 00:46:53.140
And so I don't want to put a
lid on someone's belief of what

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:57.310
they could achieve because
they have a disability.

00:46:57.310 --> 00:46:59.200
So I think your
question for me really

00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:03.310
provokes a couple of
different areas of thinking.

00:47:03.310 --> 00:47:08.470
When I did start going to
classes with disabled kids,

00:47:08.470 --> 00:47:11.477
and then went to camps
with disabled kids,

00:47:11.477 --> 00:47:13.060
and in the future,
you're going to see

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:17.050
a film that's going to come
out probably in 2019 or 2020

00:47:17.050 --> 00:47:18.720
called Crip Camp.

00:47:18.720 --> 00:47:21.610
And when it comes out,
Harvard will a great place

00:47:21.610 --> 00:47:24.430
to come in and do a previewing.

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:26.800
The reason I raise
this is because it

00:47:26.800 --> 00:47:29.230
was a segregated camp.

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:32.140
The reason it existed
was because those

00:47:32.140 --> 00:47:35.620
of us with disabilities couldn't
go to the regular camps.

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:42.220
But what was very valuable about
the well run disabled camps--

00:47:42.220 --> 00:47:45.010
and in this case
camp Jeanette-- was

00:47:45.010 --> 00:47:49.870
run by 1960s hippies who were
progressive, drug smoking

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:52.510
guys and gals.

00:47:52.510 --> 00:47:53.860
None of whom had disabilities.

00:47:53.860 --> 00:48:00.290
But were in fact into
a free love approach.

00:48:00.290 --> 00:48:04.180
But it allowed us an
opportunity as disabled people

00:48:04.180 --> 00:48:08.020
to really begin to come
together and think in a way

00:48:08.020 --> 00:48:10.540
that we hadn't been
able to before.

00:48:10.540 --> 00:48:13.570
I, like many other people,
have only one disabled person

00:48:13.570 --> 00:48:15.340
in the family, it was me.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:18.370
And my parents were
really fighting for me

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:21.480
to be able to become
included in society,

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:23.380
but they understood
discrimination.

00:48:23.380 --> 00:48:26.890
I mean they're Jewish, they
experienced anti-Semitism,

00:48:26.890 --> 00:48:29.350
their families were
killed in the Holocaust.

00:48:29.350 --> 00:48:32.780
But disability is something
a little bit different.

00:48:32.780 --> 00:48:35.200
And so the ability
to come together

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:38.260
with other disabled
people and really

00:48:38.260 --> 00:48:42.810
just to begin to talk
about how our lives were

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:45.960
different than our
brothers and our sisters

00:48:45.960 --> 00:48:47.970
and our cousins
and our neighbors.

00:48:47.970 --> 00:48:52.080
How as we're getting older we
couldn't go across the street,

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:53.970
we couldn't get on a bus.

00:48:53.970 --> 00:48:59.970
We didn't have technology
or Braille or sign language

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:03.150
interpreters or
whatever it might be.

00:49:03.150 --> 00:49:05.910
We were not able to
begin to really think

00:49:05.910 --> 00:49:10.060
about becoming a part of the
quote, unquote, American dream.

00:49:10.060 --> 00:49:13.170
And so it was really
important for us

00:49:13.170 --> 00:49:17.040
to do what many
people considered

00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:19.810
beyond the realm of possibility.

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:24.150
And so I want to encourage
people to think broadly.

00:49:24.150 --> 00:49:26.430
Not by themselves,
although everyone

00:49:26.430 --> 00:49:29.970
has to have their own personal
vision of what they want

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:33.120
for their life, but
also to be able to work

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:37.260
with other people who have
disabilities and others who've

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:41.040
been a part of other movements
who've fought for equality

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:43.500
and are continuing to
fight for equality.

00:49:43.500 --> 00:49:46.150
How we can learn
from each other.

00:49:46.150 --> 00:49:51.330
And at the same time, I think
it's also very important

00:49:51.330 --> 00:49:54.110
that we address,
I don't know, you

00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:55.950
know the issue of
super crip, I know

00:49:55.950 --> 00:49:59.400
we can have a very long
discussion about that.

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:06.030
I think, Superman, before
Reeves acquired a disability,

00:50:06.030 --> 00:50:08.040
people loved Superman.

00:50:08.040 --> 00:50:11.130
When Supergirl or superwoman
or whatever she was called

00:50:11.130 --> 00:50:14.220
came forward, now Wonder
Woman, we love that.

00:50:14.220 --> 00:50:17.850
So why can't a disabled
person be a Wonder Woman?

00:50:17.850 --> 00:50:21.930
I mean, I think that's what
we're not wanting to say,

00:50:21.930 --> 00:50:24.710
that all people,
disabled are not,

00:50:24.710 --> 00:50:27.480
are super anything,
because we're not.

00:50:27.480 --> 00:50:30.210
But I want to make
sure that people really

00:50:30.210 --> 00:50:34.830
can believe that we can
excel, we can be super.

00:50:34.830 --> 00:50:39.270
The issue of religion, I
think, is very important.

00:50:39.270 --> 00:50:41.220
I think we need to
be doing a lot more

00:50:41.220 --> 00:50:43.560
with the religious communities.

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:45.600
And I think we see
in the United States

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:48.240
there is some more work
going on in that area

00:50:48.240 --> 00:50:49.210
and around the world.

00:50:49.210 --> 00:50:51.400
But I really think
it's important.

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:55.380
It's important because we want
religious leaders to be looking

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:57.780
at what the role of
religion in their countries

00:50:57.780 --> 00:51:01.110
can be playing in the
area of disability.

00:51:01.110 --> 00:51:03.840
That we are opening doors
so the disabled people

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:06.870
can become a part of whatever
the religious community is

00:51:06.870 --> 00:51:07.950
offering.

00:51:07.950 --> 00:51:10.590
Not that we're a
curse of or blessed

00:51:10.590 --> 00:51:13.410
by, but that we are part of.

00:51:13.410 --> 00:51:16.120
And that as religious
communities,

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:19.710
we need to be putting
our hands forth

00:51:19.710 --> 00:51:23.940
to help ensure that all people
are able to make contributions.

00:51:23.940 --> 00:51:27.570
So I think, obviously, the
issue of being from the divine

00:51:27.570 --> 00:51:30.480
is not where we
want to be pursuing,

00:51:30.480 --> 00:51:34.170
but we need to be able
to enter into a discourse

00:51:34.170 --> 00:51:37.350
with the leaders who are putting
that forward to really allow

00:51:37.350 --> 00:51:39.690
people to understand this.

00:51:39.690 --> 00:51:44.790
I was in Algeria once and I
was at a wheelchair basketball

00:51:44.790 --> 00:51:45.570
game.

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:48.090
And there was an
Imam in a wheelchair,

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:51.930
and someone introduced us
and we started talking.

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:55.230
And the media wanted to know
why was I speaking to him?

00:51:55.230 --> 00:51:57.060
Well I was talking
to him because he

00:51:57.060 --> 00:51:59.200
was a religious leader
in the community.

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:01.390
He was also a basketball player.

00:52:01.390 --> 00:52:03.510
And he could play a
very important role.

00:52:03.510 --> 00:52:07.890
So reaching out into our
communities and learning more

00:52:07.890 --> 00:52:11.220
and getting them
to be advocates.

00:52:11.220 --> 00:52:16.500
To see us as members of the
community who can contribute.

00:52:16.500 --> 00:52:19.590
Not who only need
help, but who can

00:52:19.590 --> 00:52:21.876
make meaningful
contributions I think

00:52:21.876 --> 00:52:23.250
is a part of where
we need to go.

00:52:26.450 --> 00:52:27.430
Question?

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:29.470
Comment?

00:52:29.470 --> 00:52:30.664
- Hello

00:52:30.664 --> 00:52:31.830
- Can you give me your name?

00:52:31.830 --> 00:52:32.350
- Yeah.

00:52:32.350 --> 00:52:33.620
Hello, good afternoon.

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:35.890
My name is Claire
Burks Dresser and I

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:37.220
don't know if you remember me.

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:40.270
We actually had a conversation
at Northern Arizona University

00:52:40.270 --> 00:52:41.530
a few years ago.

00:52:41.530 --> 00:52:42.230
- OK, great.

00:52:42.230 --> 00:52:44.470
- And you gave me
some advice on how

00:52:44.470 --> 00:52:47.320
to go into the
international community

00:52:47.320 --> 00:52:49.300
to advocate for
disability issues.

00:52:49.300 --> 00:52:50.920
And I'm happy to say
that these days I

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:55.730
work in refugee resettlement
advocating for disability.

00:52:55.730 --> 00:53:00.010
So in that field I'm seeing
some resistance, some hesitancy,

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:02.530
and talking about disability
for resettled refugees

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:04.700
once they arrive to
the United States.

00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:07.150
There's this closed
atmosphere where

00:53:07.150 --> 00:53:10.150
talking about disability, maybe
in their world experiences,

00:53:10.150 --> 00:53:14.800
maybe as someone who
has left a crisis,

00:53:14.800 --> 00:53:17.260
it has been safer not
to talk about disability

00:53:17.260 --> 00:53:19.120
or has been put on
the side as they've

00:53:19.120 --> 00:53:22.370
been escaping persecution.

00:53:22.370 --> 00:53:26.350
So these days I'd like to have
more conversation with families

00:53:26.350 --> 00:53:30.040
who are still struggling to
talk about disability now

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:32.260
that they're here in
the United States.

00:53:32.260 --> 00:53:34.900
Do you have some thoughts on
how I can have those opening

00:53:34.900 --> 00:53:38.290
conversations to folks who
might be a little resistant

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:42.340
to disclose disability
or really invite it

00:53:42.340 --> 00:53:43.850
as a greater conversation?

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:45.840
- So let me ask you to
answer that question.

00:53:49.310 --> 00:53:51.810
And I'm having to
jump in, but how would

00:53:51.810 --> 00:53:56.320
you like to pursue that?

00:53:56.320 --> 00:53:58.150
- Well I think,
for me, as someone

00:53:58.150 --> 00:54:00.370
who has a physical disability
but only growing up

00:54:00.370 --> 00:54:04.240
in the United States, the
trouble that I've faced so far

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:07.570
is trying to connect to
a different experience

00:54:07.570 --> 00:54:09.220
across the globe.

00:54:09.220 --> 00:54:11.860
But the thing that
connects us is

00:54:11.860 --> 00:54:15.340
as you said, the challenges
that come with disability.

00:54:15.340 --> 00:54:22.060
But I think what I'd like to do
is create an atmosphere where

00:54:22.060 --> 00:54:24.490
they can talk freely and safely.

00:54:24.490 --> 00:54:29.050
Where universal design is
an expectation upon coming

00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:30.790
to the United States.

00:54:30.790 --> 00:54:32.650
But the issue that
I come across is

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:35.710
because we talk about
disability more than we

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:39.640
have in terms of inclusivity,
but it's still a long way

00:54:39.640 --> 00:54:40.760
to go.

00:54:40.760 --> 00:54:44.170
There are still challenges
in creating spaces,

00:54:44.170 --> 00:54:47.530
even amongst people who
work in nonprofit to have

00:54:47.530 --> 00:54:49.400
those conversations.

00:54:49.400 --> 00:54:52.540
So I would like to
have a space where

00:54:52.540 --> 00:54:56.990
folks can talk about disability
when they come as refugees.

00:54:56.990 --> 00:54:59.140
But I'm still facing
the challenges

00:54:59.140 --> 00:55:02.350
where even the United States
staff might put it off

00:55:02.350 --> 00:55:05.650
to the side or it might not be
a priority because there are so

00:55:05.650 --> 00:55:09.340
many intersectional issues and
things that are not exclusively

00:55:09.340 --> 00:55:11.930
about disability, such
as refugee [INAUDIBLE]..

00:55:11.930 --> 00:55:15.040
- So the reason I asked
you to answer the question

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:20.030
is because you experience
this on a day to day basis.

00:55:20.030 --> 00:55:22.480
And I think that's
very important.

00:55:22.480 --> 00:55:24.632
And you are telling a story.

00:55:24.632 --> 00:55:25.840
And I think that's important.

00:55:25.840 --> 00:55:29.530
And I really think
it's important to share

00:55:29.530 --> 00:55:33.370
with the families that you're
working with your experiences.

00:55:33.370 --> 00:55:35.500
And to allow people
to understand

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:38.080
that there are opportunities
in the United States,

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:40.490
but there are also challenges.

00:55:40.490 --> 00:55:42.340
And I think it's
important to try

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:46.300
to see which other organizations
in the communities,

00:55:46.300 --> 00:55:50.290
like centers for independent
living or other parent groups,

00:55:50.290 --> 00:55:54.160
or depending on the issues that
are going on with the families,

00:55:54.160 --> 00:55:58.060
that they're also brought
in so that people, in fact,

00:55:58.060 --> 00:56:04.720
can expand their universe to be
able to also meet other refugee

00:56:04.720 --> 00:56:07.490
families who have
disabled people.

00:56:07.490 --> 00:56:09.820
And some organizations
around the United States

00:56:09.820 --> 00:56:12.010
are doing a better job
than others on this.

00:56:12.010 --> 00:56:13.810
But I think what's
very important is

00:56:13.810 --> 00:56:17.830
you've put a finger on
a very critical issue.

00:56:17.830 --> 00:56:23.370
And that is that people who
are coming from other countries

00:56:23.370 --> 00:56:26.640
also may not have very
high expectations,

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:30.670
may have no expectations
about what can happen here.

00:56:30.670 --> 00:56:32.970
And so I think it really
is important to help

00:56:32.970 --> 00:56:37.410
people learn about what
opportunities are here.

00:56:37.410 --> 00:56:39.420
And to also be a part
of the discussion that's

00:56:39.420 --> 00:56:41.940
going on that disabled
refugees coming here

00:56:41.940 --> 00:56:43.569
are falling through the cracks.

00:56:43.569 --> 00:56:45.360
They're not learning
about the systems that

00:56:45.360 --> 00:56:47.610
are out there for
them and identifying

00:56:47.610 --> 00:56:51.120
other disabled refugees who've
been in the United States

00:56:51.120 --> 00:56:52.970
for longer periods of time.

00:56:52.970 --> 00:56:54.720
And I'm happy to talk
with you about that.

00:56:54.720 --> 00:56:56.760
I'm sure there are other
people in the room also,

00:56:56.760 --> 00:56:58.260
but to give you
some names of people

00:56:58.260 --> 00:56:59.760
that you may want to speak to.

00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:01.840
But this is a very
important issue.

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:04.560
And it's not just in the
refugee area, you know,

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:06.820
you can pick many
other subjects.

00:57:06.820 --> 00:57:13.180
So using your voice and your
knowledge I think is important.

00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:16.310
And being a driver
within your organization,

00:57:16.310 --> 00:57:20.780
within the refugee community
providers of services.

00:57:20.780 --> 00:57:24.050
And also looking at
opportunities where refugees

00:57:24.050 --> 00:57:28.970
may be coming together in
religious organizations,

00:57:28.970 --> 00:57:33.050
in schools, social
workers, really

00:57:33.050 --> 00:57:36.230
trying to give people
space and knowledge

00:57:36.230 --> 00:57:38.660
and knowing that you're
there and that they can

00:57:38.660 --> 00:57:40.610
speak to you when they need to.

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:43.590
If that's possible, I think,
is also very important.

00:57:43.590 --> 00:57:47.000
And remember I think, in
my view, 100% of refugees

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:48.214
have disabilities.

00:57:48.214 --> 00:57:49.880
They've been fleeing
their country, that

00:57:49.880 --> 00:57:54.080
get psychosocial disabilities,
they may not, in fact, even

00:57:54.080 --> 00:57:54.590
know it.

00:57:54.590 --> 00:57:57.200
And so I think there
are people like us who

00:57:57.200 --> 00:58:00.140
have more visible disabilities.

00:58:00.140 --> 00:58:03.890
But even those of us with
more visible disabilities

00:58:03.890 --> 00:58:05.580
also have other issues going on.

00:58:05.580 --> 00:58:08.480
So I think it needs to be a part
of the bigger discourse that's

00:58:08.480 --> 00:58:10.730
going on around
refugee settlement.

00:58:10.730 --> 00:58:13.669
And I want to see you,
I can't see you now,

00:58:13.669 --> 00:58:14.960
look forward to talking to you.

00:58:14.960 --> 00:58:15.170
Oh, there you are.

00:58:15.170 --> 00:58:16.100
I see your hand.

00:58:16.100 --> 00:58:16.899
OK.

00:58:16.899 --> 00:58:18.440
Congratulations on
what you're doing.

